        <p data-uuid="d213beec41bd43d3a22255e4c14915a9">By 1500 European culture had been shaped by
            centuries of civilization and cultural development. Among the most significant
            and lasting contributions were those made by the ancient Greeks and Romans.<br />
        </p>
        <h3 data-uuid="517bb41b3f404afcb5e550188928c1f8">Greek Philosophers and Government</h3>
        <p data-uuid="0a28aefdd11b475e9e1ac7939392760e">Ancient Greeks valued
            human reason and believed in the power of the human mind to think, explain, and
            understand life. Three of the greatest Greek thinkers, or philosophers, were
            Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle. <b><dfn title="Socrates">Socrates</dfn></b>, a great teacher, wanted
            to make people think and question their own beliefs. <b><dfn title="Plato">Plato</dfn></b>, a
            philosopher and teacher, wrote a work called <i>The Republic</i>. It describes
            an ideal society based on justice and fairness for everyone. <b><dfn title="Aristotle">Aristotle</dfn></b>
            taught that people should live their lives based on <b><dfn title="reason">reason</dfn></b>, or clear
            and ordered thinking.</p>
        <section data-uuid="ad0b5cc199424223a7c5271a4bdb5586" class="image-carousel">
